420
00:31:27,465 --> 00:31:29,933
-Aye.
-Ya mean ya know it?

421
00:31:30,001 --> 00:31:32,731
Why didn't ya tell me?
Did ya see them?

422
00:31:32,804 --> 00:31:35,068
-Aye.
-Tell me about them.

423
00:31:35,140 --> 00:31:37,074
What are they like?
How do they look?

424
00:31:37,142 --> 00:31:40,373
''He has brownish hair,
a wee bit taller than father.''

425
00:31:40,445 --> 00:31:43,175
-Very nice face.
-What about the other one?

426
00:31:43,248 --> 00:31:46,012
''The other? He's about
the same, l imagine.''

427
00:31:46,084 --> 00:31:48,882
l really cannot remember.
l only saw them for a moment.

428
00:31:48,954 --> 00:31:50,888
Where are they?
Where did they go?

429
00:31:50,956 --> 00:31:54,289
To the square for some food.
They've probably left by now.

430
00:31:59,898 --> 00:32:02,389
Maybe they haven't.
l'm goin' to see.

431
00:32:02,467 --> 00:32:04,458
l'll pick up the bread for ya.

432
00:32:05,904 --> 00:32:08,395
Jean! Are you daft?

433
00:32:08,473 --> 00:32:10,805
How can you even think
of goin' out today?

434
00:32:10,875 --> 00:32:12,900
Supposin' you run into Charlie.

435
00:32:12,978 --> 00:32:16,175
Do you want to start out your marriage
under a cloud of bad luck?

436
00:32:16,248 --> 00:32:18,341
''-l'll get the bread.
-Oh, but, Fiona--''

437
00:32:18,416 --> 00:32:21,579
Who ever heard of a bride bein' seen
on the day of her weddin'?

438
00:32:21,653 --> 00:32:24,087
l'm surprised at you
for even thinkin' of it.

439
00:32:44,909 --> 00:32:46,342
Lovely.

440
00:32:55,854 --> 00:33:00,154
''Oh, you're a winnin' lad.
A right winnin' lad!''

441
00:33:00,225 --> 00:33:02,193
''You've noticed that, have you?''

442
00:33:03,061 --> 00:33:04,619
Do you have a wife?

443
00:33:05,997 --> 00:33:09,057
l never touch the stuff.
l don't believe in marriage.

444
00:33:09,134 --> 00:33:11,568
l've seen too many happy love affairs
broken up by it.

445
00:33:11,636 --> 00:33:14,833
''Oh, you're a braw and handsome lad,
Mr. Douglas.''

446
00:33:14,906 --> 00:33:17,670
You should see me when l'm rested.
l'm almost robust.

447
00:33:23,281 --> 00:33:25,647
We do not have enough lads
in Brigadoon.

448
00:33:25,717 --> 00:33:28,277
''Enough for everybody else,
or enough for you?''

449
00:33:28,353 --> 00:33:30,617
There are so few single lads
in town.

450
00:33:30,689 --> 00:33:32,816
lt's hard for a lass
to catch a husband.

451
00:33:32,891 --> 00:33:36,327
lt would be so nice if ya
could stay a while. Could ya?

452
00:33:36,394 --> 00:33:38,328
l'll have to ask my pop.

453
00:33:44,235 --> 00:33:46,430
We came over here to hunt grouse.

454
00:33:46,504 --> 00:33:48,438
And coming from this hill--

455
00:33:49,908 --> 00:33:51,899
''-Oh.
-Good mornin', dearie.''

456
00:33:51,976 --> 00:33:53,910
Father asked me
to remind ya...

457
00:33:53,978 --> 00:33:56,378
to be sure and come sign
the family Bible this afternoon.

458
00:33:56,448 --> 00:33:58,040
l'll be over.

459
00:33:58,116 --> 00:34:01,051
''-How was breakfast, sir?
-Wonderful. Thanks.''

460
00:34:03,021 --> 00:34:04,784
Where's my bride?

461
00:34:04,856 --> 00:34:06,118
She's home...

462
00:34:07,192 --> 00:34:08,420
palpitatin'.

463
00:34:09,160 --> 00:34:11,151
lsn't that your bride?

464
00:34:11,229 --> 00:34:14,164
''No, lad.
That's her older sister, Fiona.''

465
00:34:21,072 --> 00:34:23,506
-Do you mind if l have more ale?
-Help yourself.

466
00:34:31,516 --> 00:34:33,643
''Here, old tank.
Amuse yourself.''

467
00:34:33,718 --> 00:34:35,652
l thought we were going hunting.

468
00:34:35,720 --> 00:34:37,051
l am.

469
00:34:39,491 --> 00:34:41,015
See you at the weddin'.

470
00:34:43,395 --> 00:34:44,794
Can l carry that for you?

471
00:34:44,863 --> 00:34:47,354
''No, thank you.
l do not have far to go with it.''

472
00:34:47,432 --> 00:34:49,423
''You're very busy today,
aren't you?''

473
00:34:49,501 --> 00:34:52,129
''-Aye, my sister--
-They told me she's getting married.''

474
00:34:53,204 --> 00:34:55,968
-l was overjoyed.
-That's very kind of ya.

475
00:34:56,040 --> 00:34:59,874
''Not at all. ln this case,
her happiness is mine.''

476
00:34:59,944 --> 00:35:02,344
''Besides, Charlie's a nice kid.''

477
00:35:02,414 --> 00:35:04,746
''Aye, he is that.''

478
00:35:04,816 --> 00:35:07,546
lt's wonderfully refreshing
these days...

479
00:35:07,619 --> 00:35:10,713
to see someone so enthusiastic
about getting married.

480
00:35:10,789 --> 00:35:13,155
-ls it so unusual?
-l think so.

481
00:35:13,224 --> 00:35:15,818
l was thinking of facing
the minister once...

482
00:35:15,894 --> 00:35:18,624
and l certainly wasn't
bubbling over like Charlie.

483
00:35:18,696 --> 00:35:20,254
Oh?

484
00:35:20,331 --> 00:35:21,491
''Oh, what?''

485
00:35:21,566 --> 00:35:23,329
l'm very surprised.

486
00:35:23,401 --> 00:35:27,337
You do not look like the sort of lad
who'd be thinkin' of settlin' down.

487
00:35:27,405 --> 00:35:31,432
l didn't say that. l just said
l was thinking of getting married.

488
00:35:31,509 --> 00:35:33,534
''Well, if ya felt that way...''

489
00:35:33,611 --> 00:35:35,579
'tis a very good thing ya didn't.

490
00:35:37,215 --> 00:35:41,914
''Yes, l suppose it was
a very good thing l didn't.''

491
00:35:45,089 --> 00:35:47,990
''-Good mornin', Fiona.
-Good day, Mrs. Maclntosh.''

492
00:35:48,059 --> 00:35:50,892
-This is--
-Albright. Tommy Albright.

493
00:35:52,730 --> 00:35:55,164
-Likewise.
-He's just passin' through.

494
00:35:56,434 --> 00:35:58,766
Where do ya come from?

495
00:35:58,837 --> 00:36:00,236
From America.

496
00:36:00,305 --> 00:36:02,432
You're an American?

497
00:36:02,507 --> 00:36:04,407
lsn't that all right?

498
00:36:04,476 --> 00:36:06,205
''Aye, of course.''

499
00:36:06,277 --> 00:36:09,303
''-The bread, Mrs. Maclntosh.
-Aye.''

500
00:36:09,380 --> 00:36:12,543
Andrew! Come to the window
and look at the stranger!

501
00:36:12,617 --> 00:36:14,209
He's an American.

502
00:36:14,285 --> 00:36:16,412
She gives us bread
for our potatoes.

503
00:36:16,488 --> 00:36:18,718
-That's nice.
-She's a very nice lady.

504
00:36:18,790 --> 00:36:20,052
'Tis just that--

505
00:36:20,124 --> 00:36:22,820
People don't come here
very often.

506
00:36:22,894 --> 00:36:25,522
Aye. You're very understandin'.

507
00:36:25,597 --> 00:36:27,758
''No, l'm not.''

508
00:36:27,832 --> 00:36:31,097
l don't understand one thing
about this place.

509
00:36:32,237 --> 00:36:36,071
The bread will be ready in an hour.
l'll bring it to your cottage.

510
00:36:36,140 --> 00:36:38,335
''-Thank you, Mrs. Maclntosh.
-Good day.''

511
00:36:38,409 --> 00:36:39,740
Good day.

512
00:36:47,785 --> 00:36:49,719
l've been wanting
to do that all day.

513
00:36:52,090 --> 00:36:53,352
Now where?

514
00:36:53,424 --> 00:36:56,825
l must gather some heather
for the weddin' decorations.

515
00:36:56,895 --> 00:36:58,556
Where do you do that?

516
00:36:58,630 --> 00:37:01,190
''On the far hill,
where the heather is.''

517
00:37:03,501 --> 00:37:05,435
Do you mind if l come along?

518
00:37:14,579 --> 00:37:17,412
-Why did ya want to?
-Why?

519
00:37:17,482 --> 00:37:19,973
''Oh, l don't know exactly.''

520
00:37:20,051 --> 00:37:23,043
Maybe it's because
l've nothing much else to do.

521
00:37:23,121 --> 00:37:26,454
Or maybe it's because l'm so
full of wonder about this place...

522
00:37:26,524 --> 00:37:28,458
and want to stay a little longer.

523
00:37:30,028 --> 00:37:32,588
Or maybe it's because
l remember how relieved l was...

524
00:37:32,664 --> 00:37:35,861
when l found out it was
your sister's wedding day and not yours.

525
00:37:41,039 --> 00:37:45,635
Can't we two
go walkin' together

526
00:37:45,710 --> 00:37:50,704
Out beyond
the valley of trees

527
00:37:50,782 --> 00:37:55,981
Out where there's
a hillside of heather

528
00:37:56,054 --> 00:38:01,822
Curtsyin' gently
in the breeze

529
00:38:01,893 --> 00:38:06,489
That's what l'd like to do

530
00:38:06,564 --> 00:38:09,624
See the heather

531
00:38:09,701 --> 00:38:14,536
But with you

532
00:38:17,709 --> 00:38:23,443
The mist of May
is in the gloamin'

533
00:38:23,514 --> 00:38:27,780
And all the clouds
are holdin' still

534
00:38:29,053 --> 00:38:33,422
So take my hand
and let's go roamin'

535
00:38:33,491 --> 00:38:39,088
Through the heather
on the hill

536
00:38:40,331 --> 00:38:45,530
The mornin' dew
is blinkin' yonder

537
00:38:45,603 --> 00:38:50,540
There's lazy music
in the rill

538
00:38:50,608 --> 00:38:54,704
And all l wanna do is wander

539
