00:55:55,198 --> 00:55:57,359
-Aren't we headin' back?
-There's no hurry.

690
00:55:57,434 --> 00:55:59,925
Let's stick around a while.
There's gonna be a wedding.

691
00:56:00,003 --> 00:56:02,699
''-Yours?
-Oh, very funny.''

692
00:56:07,110 --> 00:56:10,079
l thought we came to Scotland
to go grouse shooting.

693
00:56:10,147 --> 00:56:13,446
l'd like to get one little bird
before the day is over.

694
00:56:13,517 --> 00:56:16,418
-What's the matter?
-Hey.

695
00:56:16,486 --> 00:56:20,047
l must be a little touched.
Listen to this.

696
00:56:20,123 --> 00:56:22,557
''''''Married: Elizabeth Lang
to Andrew Campbell...''

697
00:56:22,626 --> 00:56:26,027
''''''July 2nd, 1719.''''''

698
00:56:26,096 --> 00:56:28,690
What about it?
People used to get married then.

699
00:56:28,765 --> 00:56:32,531
''No, wait a minute.
''''Children: Fiona.''

700
00:56:32,602 --> 00:56:36,470
''''''Born October 10th, 1732.''

701
00:56:36,540 --> 00:56:40,943
''''''Jean. Born April 8th, 1736.''''''

702
00:56:41,011 --> 00:56:42,638
Well?

703
00:56:42,713 --> 00:56:46,979
Fiona told me Jean's four years younger.

704
00:56:47,050 --> 00:56:49,610
-Well?
-They're the sisters in this Bible!

705
00:56:49,686 --> 00:56:53,713
That's ridiculous.
They're probably just named after them.

706
00:56:53,790 --> 00:56:57,419
''-You know Charlie's last name, right?
-Dalrymple, isn't it?''

707
00:56:57,494 --> 00:56:59,485
''Dalrymple, yes.
Get this.''

708
00:56:59,563 --> 00:57:02,031
''''''Married: Jean Campbell to
Charles Chisholm Dalrymple...''

709
00:57:02,099 --> 00:57:06,058
''''''May 24th, 1754.''''''

710
00:57:07,671 --> 00:57:10,037
Now what do you say?

711
00:57:10,107 --> 00:57:12,041
Congratulations.

712
00:57:14,277 --> 00:57:17,041
l don't understand.

713
00:57:17,114 --> 00:57:19,480
No Brigadoon on the map.

714
00:57:20,717 --> 00:57:24,380
All those odd things that happened when
l was out with Fiona this afternoon...

715
00:57:24,454 --> 00:57:28,220
all that stuff about a miracle...

716
00:57:28,291 --> 00:57:30,225
and now this.

717
00:57:40,070 --> 00:57:42,231
Why are you getting so worked up?

718
00:57:43,440 --> 00:57:47,706
''lf it makes 'em happy to disregard
200 years of human bing-bang, let 'em.''

719
00:57:47,778 --> 00:57:51,305
''There must be a logical explanation
for this, logical enough even for you.''

720
00:57:51,381 --> 00:57:54,544
You don't have to explain
anything to me. l don't care.

721
00:57:58,855 --> 00:58:01,380
What's the matter?

722
00:58:01,458 --> 00:58:04,655
ls that your name
in this Bible?

723
00:58:04,728 --> 00:58:05,717
Aye.

724
00:58:05,796 --> 00:58:08,526
Someone seems to have
messed up your book.

725
00:58:09,699 --> 00:58:13,066
What does it mean?
You must tell me.

726
00:58:13,136 --> 00:58:15,696
''There is an explanation for it,
isn't there?''

727
00:58:15,772 --> 00:58:18,935
''Aye, there is,
but l cannot tell ya.''

728
00:58:19,009 --> 00:58:22,206
ls there anybody who can?
l've got to know.

729
00:58:22,279 --> 00:58:24,804
-You must talk with the dominie.
-Who?

730
00:58:24,881 --> 00:58:26,815
''Our schoolmaster, Mr. Lundie.''

731
00:58:26,883 --> 00:58:29,545
''-Where does he live?
-Down the road in a tree, maybe.''

732
00:58:29,619 --> 00:58:34,522
''He does not live in a tree, Mr. Douglas.
Mr. Lundie's a great man.''

733
00:58:34,591 --> 00:58:37,526
''All right, Tommy,
l'll take you to him.''

734
00:58:42,299 --> 00:58:44,563
l hadn't wanted to...

735
00:58:44,634 --> 00:58:49,333
because it'll be so hard
for you to believe what you'll hear.

736
00:58:50,473 --> 00:58:52,134
And l wanted--

737
00:58:53,410 --> 00:58:56,379
l wanted you to stay with me...

738
00:58:56,446 --> 00:58:58,641
'til the end of our day.

739
00:59:07,390 --> 00:59:09,790
Take us to see Mr. Lundie.

740
00:59:11,494 --> 00:59:12,688
Aye.

741
00:59:12,762 --> 00:59:16,493
''ls it informal,
or should l wear my Napoleon hat?''

742
00:59:55,071 --> 00:59:56,868
''Good day, Mr. Lundie.''

743
00:59:56,940 --> 01:00:00,239
''Why, hello, Fiona.
What a pleasant surprise.''

744
01:00:00,310 --> 01:00:03,370
''Mr. Lundie, l'd like you
to meet Mr. Tommy Albright...''

745
01:00:03,446 --> 01:00:05,880
and Mr. Jeff Douglas.

746
01:00:05,949 --> 01:00:07,974
''-Good afternoon, gentlemen.
-How do you do, sir?''

747
01:00:08,051 --> 01:00:10,576
Good afternoon.

748
01:00:10,654 --> 01:00:12,781
Where do you gentlemen come from?

749
01:00:12,856 --> 01:00:14,847
-We're from New York.
-New York?

750
01:00:14,925 --> 01:00:17,325
We changed it from New Amsterdam.

751
01:00:17,394 --> 01:00:20,420
-So l understand.
-The British changed it.

752
01:00:20,497 --> 01:00:23,261
''Confidentially, though, as soon as
Washington organizes himself...''

753
01:00:23,333 --> 01:00:25,699
''we're gonna chase them out,
but keep it under your hat.''

754
01:00:25,769 --> 01:00:27,703
''Put a cork in it,
will you, Jeff?''

755
01:00:27,771 --> 01:00:30,239
''Mr. Lundie, l was wonderin'
if you'd be good enough...''

756
01:00:30,307 --> 01:00:32,707
to tell these gentlemen
about Brigadoon.

757
01:00:32,776 --> 01:00:35,108
They've heard and
they've seen a great deal...

758
01:00:35,178 --> 01:00:37,271
and they're very perplexed indeed.

759
01:00:37,347 --> 01:00:40,714
-Perplexed is right.
-l would very much like him--

760
01:00:40,784 --> 01:00:44,618
l mean them--to know.

761
01:00:44,688 --> 01:00:47,088
l see.

762
01:00:47,157 --> 01:00:50,957
''-Will you not be seated, gentlemen?
-Thank you.''

763
01:00:51,027 --> 01:00:54,428
''From what l gather, nobody can talk
about the place around here but you.''

764
01:00:54,497 --> 01:00:57,398
''-ls that right?
-No, that's wrong.''

765
01:00:57,467 --> 01:00:59,662
Mr. Forsythe could've told ya.

766
01:00:59,736 --> 01:01:03,570
''Forsythe? l've heard about him,
but l didn't meet him.''

767
01:01:03,640 --> 01:01:06,871
Likely not.
l think he's dead.

768
01:01:06,943 --> 01:01:09,537
''That would stand in the way,
l suppose.''

769
01:01:09,612 --> 01:01:13,548
''Let me warn you that what l'm goin'
to tell ya, ya will not believe.''

770
01:01:13,616 --> 01:01:17,609
That's all right.
We've already been warned.

771
01:01:17,687 --> 01:01:19,348
Why won't we believe it?

772
01:01:19,422 --> 01:01:23,222
Because what happened
in Brigadoon was a miracle...

773
01:01:23,293 --> 01:01:26,194
and most folks
do not believe in miracles.

774
01:01:26,262 --> 01:01:30,790
''Miracles require faith,
and faith seems to be as dead as--''

775
01:01:30,867 --> 01:01:33,233
Mr. Forsythe?

776
01:01:33,303 --> 01:01:34,497
Aye.

777
01:01:34,571 --> 01:01:38,268
Now this miracle happened--
Let me see.

778
01:01:38,341 --> 01:01:40,468
-What day is it?
-Friday.

779
01:01:40,543 --> 01:01:46,140
Friday. That means it happened
exactly 200 years ago.

780
01:01:46,216 --> 01:01:50,710
Two hundred years ago the Highlands
of Scotland were plagued with witches--

781
01:01:50,787 --> 01:01:53,517
wicked sorcerers who were
takin' the Scottish people...

782
01:01:53,590 --> 01:01:58,289
away from the teachings of God
and puttin' the devil into their souls.

783
01:01:58,361 --> 01:02:02,559
''They were indeed
horrible, destructive women.''

784
01:02:02,632 --> 01:02:06,090
-l do not suppose you have such women.
-Witches?

785
01:02:06,169 --> 01:02:08,899
''Oh, we have 'em.
We pronounce it differently.''

786
01:02:08,972 --> 01:02:12,169
lt did not matter that
they were not real sorcerers...

787
01:02:12,242 --> 01:02:14,608
because you and l know
there's no such thing...

788
01:02:14,677 --> 01:02:18,477
but their influence
was very real indeed.

789
01:02:19,582 --> 01:02:21,846
Now we had at that time
in Brigadoon...

790
01:02:21,918 --> 01:02:24,409
an old minister of the kirk...

791
01:02:24,487 --> 01:02:26,455
named Mr. Forsythe...

792
01:02:26,523 --> 01:02:29,617
and a good man he was.

793
01:02:29,692 --> 01:02:33,287
-The kindest man in Scotland.
-l believe he was.

794
01:02:33,363 --> 01:02:37,527
No man loved his parish
as did Mr. Forsythe...

795
01:02:37,600 --> 01:02:41,263
''but he was gettin' old,
and it grieved him that one day soon...''

796
01:02:41,337 --> 01:02:44,033
he'd have to leave
those he loved so well.

797
01:02:44,107 --> 01:02:46,735
But most of all
he worried about the witches.

798
01:02:46,810 --> 01:02:49,745
''Now mind you, they hadn't
visited us as yet in Brigadoon...''

799
01:02:49,813 --> 01:02:53,977
but he knew that there was
a band of them coming our way.

800
01:02:55,185 --> 01:02:58,348
So he began to wonder whether
there was not something he could do...

801
01:02:58,421 --> 01:03:02,482
''to protect the folk of his parish,
not only against them...''

802
01:03:02,559 --> 01:03:05,289
but against all the evils
that might come to Brigadoon...

803
01:03:05,361 --> 01:03:08,387
from the outside world
after he died.

804
01:03:08,465 --> 01:03:11,662
Then one day he came to me
and told me...

805
01:03:11,734 --> 01:03:15,864
that he had decided
to ask God for a miracle.

806
01:03:15,939 --> 01:03:20,740
''And on an early Wednesday mornin',
right after midnight...''

807
01:03:20,810 --> 01:03:24,439
he went out to a hill
beyond Brigadoon...

808
01:03:24,514 --> 01:03:27,915
and made his prayer to God.

809
01:03:27,984 --> 01:03:32,011
''And there, in the hush
of the sleeping world...''

810
01:03:32,088 --> 01:03:35,319
he asked God that night
to make Brigadoon...

811
01:03:35,391 --> 01:03:38,121
and all the people in it...

812
01:03:38,194 --> 01:03:42,153
vanish into the highland mist.

813
01:03:42,232 --> 01:03:44,757
Vanish...

814
01:03:44,834 --> 01:03:46,859
but not for always.

815
01:03:46,936 --> 01:03:50,133
They would return
just as they were for one day...

816
01:03:50,206 --> 01:03:52,606
every hundred years.

817
01:03:52,675 --> 01:03:55,405
The people would lead
their customary lives...

818
01:03:55,478 --> 01:03:58,311
but every day when they awoke...

819
01:03:58,381 --> 01:04:01,509
it would be a hundred years later.

820
01:04:01,584 --> 01:04:05,350
And when we awoke next day...

821
01:04:05,421 --> 01:04:09,380
it was a hundred years later.

822
01:04:11,794 --> 01:04:13,989
''ln this way,
Mr. Forsythe figured that...''

823
01:04:14,063 --> 01:04:16,293
there'd be no change
in the lives of the people.

824
01:04:16,366 --> 01:04:21,235
They just wouldn't be in any century
long enough to be touched by it.

825
01:04:21,304 --> 01:04:23,067
You mean that--

826
01:04:23,139 --> 01:04:25,334
You mean that you
go to bed at night...

827
01:04:25,408 --> 01:04:28,866
''and when you wake up the next day,
it's a hundred years later?''

828
01:04:28,945 --> 01:04:30,207
Aye.

829
01:04:31,314 --> 01:04:33,874
And every day
is a hundred years later?

830
01:04:33,950 --> 01:04:35,110
Aye.

831
01:04:35,185 --> 01:04:37,244
What happened to the minister?

832
01:04:38,488 --> 01:04:40,422
We ne'er saw him again.

833
01:04:40,490 --> 01:04:43,687
''You see, he realized
to ask for such a miracle...''

834
01:04:43,760 --> 01:04:47,924
''some sacrifice would have to be made,
and he wanted to be the one to make it.''

835
01:04:47,997 --> 01:04:53,060
''Well, what was the greatest
sacrifice that he could offer?''

836
01:04:53,136 --> 01:04:56,799
lt was to be separated from
those he loved before his time.

837
01:04:56,873 --> 01:05:01,173
And that was why he went out
to a hill beyond Brigadoon...

838
01:05:01,244 --> 01:05:04,338
''where, his miracle granted...''

839
01:05:04,414 --> 01:05:07,144
he'd ne'er see Brigadoon again.

840
01:05:08,251 --> 01:05:11,482
All this happened
200 years ago?

841
01:05:11,554 --> 01:05:12,885
''Aye, lad.''

842
01:05:12,956 --> 01:05:16,119
''Which of course to us, you see,
is only two days ago.''

843
01:05:16,192 --> 01:05:18,558
Let me ask you something.

844
01:05:20,163 --> 01:05:24,099
Suppose somebody around here
got fed up and wanted to leave?

845
01:05:24,167 --> 01:05:26,135
''-Then what?
-Well, he cannot leave.''

846
01:05:26,202 --> 01:05:30,434
''-You mean, l've gotta stay here now?
-No, lad.''

847
01:05:30,506 --> 01:05:32,974
But according to Mr. Forsythe's
contract with God...

848
01:05:33,042 --> 01:05:36,443
if anyone belonging
to Brigadoon leaves...

849
01:05:36,512 --> 01:05:39,037
the enchantment
will be broken for all.

850
01:05:40,316 --> 01:05:43,717
''And that night,
when all the people go to sleep...''

851
01:05:43,786 --> 01:05:47,222
Brigadoon will disappear forever.

852
01:05:50,093 --> 01:05:53,961
''Look, l'm not saying
l believe all this...''

853
01:05:54,030 --> 01:05:56,498
butjust for argument's sake...

854
01:05:56,566 --> 01:05:58,864
suppose a stranger like--

855
01:05:58,935 --> 01:06:01,301
''well, like me--''

856
01:06:01,371 --> 01:06:04,568
came to Brigadoon
and wanted to stay.

857
01:06:04,641 --> 01:06:06,074
Could he?

858
01:06:08,311 --> 01:06:12,338
''Aye, he could.
Mr. Forsythe provided for that.''

859
01:06:12,415 --> 01:06:14,440
''He didn't miss a trick, did he?''

860
01:06:14,517 --> 01:06:16,712
''No, lad, he did not.''

861
01:06:16,786 --> 01:06:19,983
A stranger can stay
if he loves someone here.

862
01:06:20,056 --> 01:06:23,856
''Not Brigadoon itself, mind you,
but someone in Brigadoon...''

863
01:06:23,926 --> 01:06:27,054
enough to be willing
to give up everything...

864
01:06:27,130 --> 01:06:29,997
to stay near that person.

865
01:06:30,066 --> 01:06:33,263
''Which is only right,
because after all, lad...''

866
01:06:33,336 --> 01:06:37,602
if you love someone
deeply enough...

867
01:06:37,674 --> 01:06:40,438
anything is possible.

868
01:06:40,510 --> 01:06:44,105
Aye. Anything is possible.

869
01:06:44,180 --> 01:06:47,377
''Oh, Fiona, shouldn't you be thinkin'
of changin' for the weddin'?''

870
01:06:47,450 --> 01:06:49,384
l had.

871
01:06:53,022 --> 01:06:56,253
''Tommy, will l see ya later?''

872
01:06:57,327 --> 01:06:59,261
l'll be there.

873
01:07:00,263 --> 01:07:02,231
l'd like to stick around...

874
01:07:02,298 --> 01:07:05,734
and see if this place evaporates
like you say.

875
01:07:05,802 --> 01:07:07,565
l must hurry now.

876
01:07:07,637 --> 01:07:09,195
''Good-bye, Mr. Lundie...''

877
01:07:10,807 --> 01:07:12,741
and thank you.

878
01:07:18,581 --> 01:07:20,879
She's a dear lassie.

879
01:07:21,884 --> 01:07:24,978
''Yes, l'm finding that out.''

880
01:07:25,054 --> 01:07:29,423
''Mr. Lundie, are you all perfectly happy
living here in this little town?''

881
01:07:29,492 --> 01:07:31,983
''Why, of course, lad.''

882
01:07:32,061 --> 01:07:36,088
''After all, sunshine can peep
through a wee hole.''

883
01:07:37,667 --> 01:07:40,898
But what's it like at night
when you go to sleep?

884
01:07:43,206 --> 01:07:46,972
For me it's like being
carried on shadowy arms...

885
01:07:47,043 --> 01:07:49,307
up to a distant cloud...

886
01:07:49,379 --> 01:07:53,406
and there l float 'til mornin'.

887
01:07:53,483 --> 01:07:55,075
And yet...

888
01:07:55,151 --> 01:07:59,383
sometimes l think
l hear strange voices.

889
01:07:59,455 --> 01:08:01,480
-Voices?
-Aye.

890
01:08:01,557 --> 01:08:05,288
They say no words
that l can remember...

891
01:08:05,361 --> 01:08:07,295
and yet...

892
01:08:07,363 --> 01:08:11,322
they're voices filled
with a fearful longin'.

893
01:08:12,835 --> 01:08:16,737
And often they seem
to call me back.

894
01:08:18,408 --> 01:08:21,935
l've pondered over it
when l was awake...

895
01:08:22,011 --> 01:08:24,571
and l think...

896
01:08:24,647 --> 01:08:29,107
l have a feelin'
l'm hearin' the outside world.

897
01:08:30,686 --> 01:08:35,316
''Oh, there must be
an awful lot of folk out there...''

898
01:08:35,391 --> 01:08:38,554
searchin'...

899
01:08:38,628 --> 01:08:40,687
for a Brigadoon.

900
01:09:54,103 --> 01:09:56,162
Buchanan!

901
01:10:36,412 --> 01:10:38,346
Douglas!

902
01:10:45,688 --> 01:10:47,781
Lindsey!

903
01:11:42,678 --> 01:11:44,612
There's goin' to be a weddin'.

904
01:12:22,418 --> 01:12:26,081
We have no minister
in Brigadoon now.

905
01:12:26,155 --> 01:12:30,057
''ln most villages,
this would be a calamitous thing...''

906
01:12:30,126 --> 01:12:32,424
but when there is
no minister present...

907
01:12:32,495 --> 01:12:36,329
''it is perfectly proper,
according to the laws of Scotland...''

908
01:12:36,399 --> 01:12:41,132
for two people to wed each other
by sincere mutual consent.

909
01:12:41,203 --> 01:12:43,467
There need be nothin' in writin'.

910
01:12:43,539 --> 01:12:45,530
All that is necessary...

911
01:12:45,608 --> 01:12:48,543
is that ye promise
to love each other...

912
01:12:48,611 --> 01:12:51,808
while ye both are on Earth.

913
01:12:51,881 --> 01:12:54,076
''Go ahead, lad.''

914
01:13:05,561 --> 01:13:09,520
l shall love ya 'til l die...

915
01:13:09,598 --> 01:13:14,035
and l'll make all effort
to be a good husband to ya.

916
01:13:14,103 --> 01:13:17,231
And so much will l try...

917
01:13:17,306 --> 01:13:20,241
to be a fine and lovin' wife.

918
01:13:23,546 --> 01:13:27,312
''-Are we married now, Mr. Lundie?
-Aye, lad, you're married.''

919
01:13:29,552 --> 01:13:31,850
''Go on, kiss her, lad.''

920
01:13:41,997 --> 01:13:45,865
''Mr. Forsythe would have liked
to have been here, l know...''

921
01:13:45,935 --> 01:13:49,393
but as long as you're both
good and true to one another...

922
01:13:49,472 --> 01:13:52,566
ya cannot fail
but live in the grace of God...

923
01:13:52,641 --> 01:13:56,133
and Mr. Forsythe could've
wished no more than that.

924
01:18:22,311 --> 01:18:25,678
All l've done
was to want ya too much.

925
01:18:50,039 --> 01:18:52,030
l'm leavin' Brigadoon!

926
01:18:52,107 --> 01:18:55,338
'Tis the end of all of us!
The miracle is over!

927
01:18:57,179 --> 01:19:00,706
''We must stop 'im! Cover the woods!
Sandy and Angus, guard the bridge!''

928
01:19:00,783 --> 01:19:03,377
''Robert, take a group
and spread out along the old kirk!''

929
01:19:03,452 --> 01:19:06,979
''Fiona, is it true?
Could he make Brigadoon disappear?''

930
01:19:07,056 --> 01:19:09,991
''Aye, if he gets away.''

931
01:19:30,012 --> 01:19:32,913
Harry Beaton!

932
01:19:32,981 --> 01:19:35,472
Harry Beaton!

933
01:19:35,551 --> 01:19:38,145
Harry Beaton

934
01:19:38,220 --> 01:19:40,154
Harry Beaton

935
01:19:51,600 --> 01:19:53,966
Run and get him
Get him

936
01:19:54,036 --> 01:19:56,800
Run and get him
Get him

937
01:19:56,872 --> 01:20:02,105
Run ye men or ye will
never see another mornin'

938
01:20:02,177 --> 01:20:04,771
Go and stop him
Stop him

939
01:20:04,847 --> 01:20:07,475
Go and stop him
Stop him

940
01:20:07,549 --> 01:20:13,078
Run ye Highland men
or ye won't get another day

941
01:20:13,155 --> 01:20:15,988
Harry Beaton!

942
01:20:21,163 --> 01:20:23,563
Harry Beaton!

943
01:20:25,000 --> 01:20:27,434
Beaton sure came this way

944
01:20:27,503 --> 01:20:30,131
'' And we cannot be
too far behind him, laddie''

945
01:20:30,205 --> 01:20:32,765
'' Ye there, head for the brae''

946
01:20:32,841 --> 01:20:35,435
'' Keep your eye open
or ye will not find him, laddie''

947
01:20:35,511 --> 01:20:38,105
l'll go down to the creek

948
01:20:38,180 --> 01:20:40,808
'' And by God, if l see him
l'll throw him in it''

949
01:20:40,883 --> 01:20:43,511
Search the hill to the peak

950
01:20:43,585 --> 01:20:48,852
'' Find him, lads
or tomorrow will never, never come''

951
01:20:48,924 --> 01:20:51,449
Run and get him
Get him

952
01:20:51,527 --> 01:20:53,461
Run and get him
Get him

953
01:20:53,529 --> 01:20:56,430
Run and get him now

954
01:20:56,498 --> 01:20:59,524
Or ye won't plow another meadow

955
01:20:59,601 --> 01:21:02,365
Go and stop him
Stop him

956
01:21:02,437 --> 01:21:04,769
Go and stop him
Stop him

957
01:21:04,840 --> 01:21:07,138
Run ye Highland men

958
01:21:07,209 --> 01:21:10,838
Or ye won't get another day

959
01:21:10,913 --> 01:21:13,211
Harry Beaton!

960
01:21:21,690 --> 01:21:23,624
Harry Beaton!

961
01:21:38,240 --> 01:21:40,936
lf he comes into sight

962
01:21:41,009 --> 01:21:43,569
Hold him fast
Many lives are depending on it

963
01:21:43,645 --> 01:21:46,205
This must not end tonight

964
01:21:46,281 --> 01:21:51,617
They must know that tomorrow
is really going to come

965
01:21:51,687 --> 01:21:54,247
Run and get him
Get him

966
01:21:54,323 --> 01:21:56,917
Run and get him
Get him

967
01:21:56,992 --> 01:21:59,290
Spread your human net

968
01:21:59,361 --> 01:22:02,194
But don't forget
that time's against ya

969
01:22:02,264 --> 01:22:04,892
Go and stop him
Stop him

970
01:22:04,967 --> 01:22:07,561
Go and stop him
Stop him

971
01:22:07,636 --> 01:22:10,161
Run ye Highland men

972
01:22:10,239 --> 01:22:14,676
Or ye won't get another day

973
01:23:10,632 --> 01:23:13,863
-How did it happen?
-He must've hit his head on a rock.

974
01:23:13,935 --> 01:23:16,267
''Ah, the poor lad!''

975
01:23:25,647 --> 01:23:29,014
''Oh, Harry, my son, my son.''

976
01:23:29,084 --> 01:23:32,281
How could ya be so ungrateful?

977
01:23:32,354 --> 01:23:35,084
''Oh, l'm so ashamed for ye.''

978
01:23:35,157 --> 01:23:37,751
l'm so ashamed for ye.

979
01:23:37,826 --> 01:23:42,126
''Look here, all of ya. There's been
enough sorrow for one weddin' night.''

980
01:23:42,197 --> 01:23:45,724
Don't tell anyone he's dead.
Just say he was stopped.

981
01:23:45,801 --> 01:23:48,292
They can find out in the mornin'.

982
01:23:57,245 --> 01:23:59,611
l'll take him to my cottage.

983
01:23:59,681 --> 01:24:01,842
No one will see him.

984
01:24:32,881 --> 01:24:35,509
''-Father, what happened?
-lt's all right. The alarm is over.''

985
01:24:35,584 --> 01:24:38,314
''-Was he hurt bad?
-No, just scratched a wee bit.''

986
01:24:38,387 --> 01:24:40,321
He'll be fine and fit
in the mornin'.

987
01:24:40,389 --> 01:24:43,187
Now let's all come back
to the weddin' supper.

988
01:24:44,459 --> 01:24:47,326
''-Aren't ya comin', Fiona?
-Aye, Father.''

989
01:24:54,202 --> 01:24:56,136
''Angus, did ya see
Tommy, the American?''

990
01:24:56,204 --> 01:24:59,731
''Aye, dearie.
l saw him cross the bridge.''

991
01:24:59,808 --> 01:25:01,867
''Angus, did he come back?''

992
01:25:01,943 --> 01:25:04,104
l did not see him.

993
01:25:54,563 --> 01:25:57,691
They stopped him just in time.
He wasn't far from the brook.

994
01:25:57,766 --> 01:26:00,530
''Yes, they told me.''

995
01:26:00,602 --> 01:26:04,197
''Oh, Fiona, when l think
what could have happened--''

996
01:26:05,440 --> 01:26:08,466
''Your whole world, gone forever.''

997
01:26:08,543 --> 01:26:12,536
l thought my world was gone.
l thought you'd left.

998
01:26:13,949 --> 01:26:16,918
Without saying good-bye to you?

999
01:26:16,985 --> 01:26:19,249
You know l wouldn't do that.

1000
01:26:19,321 --> 01:26:21,255
l know ya wouldn't have.

1001
01:26:31,233 --> 01:26:33,292
''Tommy, darlin'.''

1002
01:28:36,691 --> 01:28:39,251
l can't leave you.

1003
01:28:39,327 --> 01:28:40,817
l can't.

1004
01:28:42,197 --> 01:28:45,598
Lundie said you could stay
if you love someone enough...

1005
01:28:45,667 --> 01:28:47,294
and l do.

1006
01:28:48,603 --> 01:28:50,628
l love you.

1007
01:28:50,705 --> 01:28:54,232
l'd better hurry and find him.
There's not much time.

1008
01:29:15,997 --> 01:29:18,557
-Are they after you now?
-l'm looking for Lundie.

1009
01:29:18,633 --> 01:29:21,693
l've got something
very important to tell you.

1010
01:29:21,770 --> 01:29:24,466
l'm not going back with you.
l'm gonna stay here.

1011
01:29:24,539 --> 01:29:26,769
''Oh, that's nice.''

1012
01:29:26,841 --> 01:29:29,537
''Please, Jeff, be serious,
just for once.''

1013
01:29:29,611 --> 01:29:32,409
l am. l'm being serious
all over the place.

1014
01:29:32,480 --> 01:29:35,779
''l tell ya, l feel more
a part of her and all this...''

1015
01:29:35,850 --> 01:29:39,013
than l ever felt about Jane
or anybody or anything back home.

1016
01:29:39,087 --> 01:29:42,648
-Great.
-l can't give it up. l belong here.

1017
01:29:42,724 --> 01:29:46,057
''Yeah, you belong here, all right.
No doubt about it.''

1018
01:29:46,127 --> 01:29:49,426
''Milking cows in the morning,
planting little things...''

1019
01:29:49,497 --> 01:29:51,556
''weaving, butter churning.''

1020
01:29:51,633 --> 01:29:54,158
''That's for you, boy.
You'll have a ball.''

1021
01:29:54,235 --> 01:29:57,693
''And just think,
you can do it for always, always...''

1022
01:29:57,772 --> 01:30:01,469
''in a town that's got one of
the longest ''''always'''' on record.''

1023
01:30:01,543 --> 01:30:05,479
lt's got nothing to do with
all these things you're talking about.

1024
01:30:05,547 --> 01:30:07,845
Don't you see?
l believe in her.

1025
01:30:07,916 --> 01:30:11,408
''And what's more, l believe
in this place, and l can't leave.''

1026
01:30:11,486 --> 01:30:14,046
''Well, kiddies,
that's what happened to Tommy today.''

1027
01:30:14,122 --> 01:30:18,081
''But what about his friend, Jeff?
Well, he had fun too.''

1028
01:30:18,159 --> 01:30:21,560
Tonight he went running off through
the woods after some Highland hothead...

1029
01:30:21,629 --> 01:30:24,063
who was gonna make
all the people disappear...

1030
01:30:24,132 --> 01:30:26,396
by crossing the wrong street.

1031
01:30:27,802 --> 01:30:30,236
''Well, after a while
Jeff thought he saw a bird...''

1032
01:30:30,305 --> 01:30:34,036
''perched low in a tree,
and he shot at it.''

1033
01:30:34,109 --> 01:30:36,407
Something fell to the ground.

1034
01:30:36,478 --> 01:30:39,936
''He rushed over to it,
and what do you think it was?''

1035
01:30:40,014 --> 01:30:41,743
lt was Hothead Harry.

1036
01:30:41,816 --> 01:30:46,913
''Yes, sir, the boy dervish himself,
lying there looking all dead.''

1037
01:30:46,988 --> 01:30:48,387
You mean you--

1038
01:30:48,456 --> 01:30:52,256
To kill somebody somewhere else in the
world would have been an awful thing.

1039
01:30:52,327 --> 01:30:56,286
But Harry was a citizen
of the little town that wasn't there...

1040
01:30:56,364 --> 01:30:58,696
and he probably never lived
in the first place.

1041
01:30:58,767 --> 01:31:01,133
''Chances are,
there weren't even any woods.''

1042
01:31:01,202 --> 01:31:04,000
''ln fact, the whole day
probably never even happened...''

1043
01:31:04,072 --> 01:31:07,439
''because, you see,
this is a fairy tale.''

1044
01:31:07,509 --> 01:31:11,445
''Oh, Jeff, you poor guy.
You must feel horrible.''

1045
01:31:11,513 --> 01:31:13,105
''What do you mean, l must feel?''

1046
01:31:13,181 --> 01:31:15,843
What am l supposed to feel
in a voodoo joint like this?

1047
01:31:15,917 --> 01:31:19,353
''Dream stuff, boy, all made up
out of broomsticks and wishing wells.''

1048
01:31:19,420 --> 01:31:22,685
lt's that or a boot camp for lunatics.
l don't know what goes on around here.

1049
01:31:22,757 --> 01:31:26,056
''All l know is that whatever it is,
it's got nothing to do with me or you...''

1050
01:31:26,127 --> 01:31:28,721
and anything that happens
to either of us just doesn't count!

1051
01:31:28,797 --> 01:31:30,924
How can it when
you don't understand it?

1052
01:31:30,999 --> 01:31:34,366
''And you want to give up your family,
your friends, your whole life for this?''

1053
01:31:34,435 --> 01:31:36,369
lt's not even worth arguing about.

1054
01:31:36,437 --> 01:31:40,533
Now go say good-bye to the little people
and thank them for the picnic.

1055
01:31:43,545 --> 01:31:46,878
''You're confused, aren't you, boy?''

1056
01:31:46,948 --> 01:31:50,782
''You know, if you believed as much
as you think you do, you wouldn't be.''

1057
01:31:55,657 --> 01:31:59,423
''Tommy, Fiona tells me
you want to stay.''

1058
01:31:59,494 --> 01:32:01,894
l'll wait for you by the bridge.

1059
01:32:03,164 --> 01:32:06,964
''Tommy, what did he mean by that?''

1060
01:32:08,036 --> 01:32:10,231
What is it?

1061
01:32:10,305 --> 01:32:13,035
''Fiona, it's me.
l thought--''

1062
01:32:18,880 --> 01:32:21,940
''Do not be ashamed
of yourself, lad.''

1063
01:32:22,016 --> 01:32:24,746
lt's the hardest thing in the world
to give everything...

1064
01:32:24,819 --> 01:32:28,050
though it's usually the only way
to get everything.

1065
01:32:33,595 --> 01:32:37,258
''You'd better hurry, Fiona.
There's not much time left.''

1066
01:32:44,839 --> 01:32:48,570
''Fiona, do you understand at all?''

1067
01:32:48,643 --> 01:32:51,703
-l think so.
-Then you're not sorry l came?

1068
01:32:51,779 --> 01:32:55,442
''No, l'm glad.
l'll be less lonely now.''

1069
01:32:55,516 --> 01:32:58,781
Real loneliness is not
bein' in love in vain...

1070
01:32:58,853 --> 01:33:01,378
but not bein' in love at all.

1071
01:33:01,456 --> 01:33:05,358
-lf l only had more time.
-lt's not your fault.

1072
01:33:09,297 --> 01:33:11,561
'Tis the end of our day!

1073
01:33:24,145 --> 01:33:27,603
''-lt isn't because l don't love you.
-l know, l know.''

1074
01:33:27,682 --> 01:33:30,173
''But to stay, l had to have
no fears and no doubts.''

1075
01:33:30,251 --> 01:33:32,185
''Aye, Tommy, aye.''

1076
01:33:53,141 --> 01:33:54,904
''Good-bye, Tommy...''

1077
01:33:54,976 --> 01:33:58,537
''and do not forget
any day, any night...''

1078
01:33:58,613 --> 01:34:01,446
that always and always...

1079
01:34:01,516 --> 01:34:03,643
l love you.

1080
01:34:03,718 --> 01:34:06,016
l love you.

1081
01:34:06,087 --> 01:34:07,987
l love you.

1082
01:34:09,057 --> 01:34:10,786
l love you.

1083
01:34:11,993 --> 01:34:13,824
l love you.

1084
01:34:39,721 --> 01:34:42,656
''Peter, Peter,
l left the dogs in the car.''

1085
01:34:42,724 --> 01:34:46,524
Will you be a dear and ask the driver
to take them home and feed them?

1086
01:34:51,632 --> 01:34:54,760
''l can't afford to get a divorce,
what with community property and taxes.''

1087
01:34:54,836 --> 01:34:57,532
-But alimony is deductible.
-But she'll want capital.

1088
01:34:57,605 --> 01:35:00,369
l can't give her that.
lt isn't fair to the children.

1089
01:35:00,441 --> 01:35:04,935
''Darling, l'm so sorry l'm late,
but l had the most agonizing afternoon.''

1090
01:35:05,013 --> 01:35:07,573
My new analyst is divine.

1091
01:35:07,648 --> 01:35:10,048
He has the most
marvelous new theory.

1092
01:35:10,118 --> 01:35:14,555
He believes that childhood
hasn't got anything to do with anything.

1093
01:35:14,622 --> 01:35:17,284
-Sounds dreamy.
-l've got my standards.

1094
01:35:17,358 --> 01:35:20,452
''l'll lie, cheat,
steal for this company...''

1095
01:35:20,528 --> 01:35:23,520
but l will not
give up my integrity.

1096
01:35:23,598 --> 01:35:27,659
l feel that a man is of value
to the organization as long as he--

1097
01:35:29,937 --> 01:35:33,304
''-Yes, it arrived this afternoon.
-Have Andre fix it for a party at 6:00.''

1098
01:35:33,374 --> 01:35:36,605
Tell him for me that if he
messes up the sauce this time--

1099
01:35:36,677 --> 01:35:40,204
''Great little car.
Hiya, Jeff.''

1100
01:35:40,281 --> 01:35:42,613
Once you get into
one of those foreign cars--

1101
01:35:42,683 --> 01:35:46,346
''But, honey, why don't you
try and see my side of it?''

1102
01:35:46,421 --> 01:35:48,355
''Frank, bring me another brandy.''

1103
01:35:48,423 --> 01:35:50,721
''-lt's bourbon, sir.
-lt is?''

1104
01:35:50,792 --> 01:35:54,319
''That's all you've had for four months,
ever since you got back from Scotland.''

1105
01:35:54,395 --> 01:35:57,592
ls that right?
l just decided l don't like it.

1106
01:35:57,665 --> 01:36:00,759
lt's not near as good as the whiskey
Mother used to make. l'll have brandy.

1107
01:36:00,835 --> 01:36:03,668
''-Yes, sir.
-Honey, l can't get home tonight.''

1108
01:36:03,738 --> 01:36:07,572
''l know, but l can't
let the boss down.''

1109
01:36:07,642 --> 01:36:10,202
He's got this girl
that he wants to take out...

1110
01:36:10,278 --> 01:36:14,612
and he needs another man along
so it won't look like she's with him.

1111
01:36:15,483 --> 01:36:17,747
''Yes, dear.''

1112
01:36:17,819 --> 01:36:20,185
''You'd better bring me
two glasses of water, Frank.''

1113
01:36:20,254 --> 01:36:24,418
''l know, baby, but we can celebrate
your birthday tomorrow night.''

1114
01:36:24,492 --> 01:36:28,622
''Honey, l can't take any longer.
l've gotta get back. Talk to you later.''

1115
01:36:28,696 --> 01:36:31,028
Frank? Sorry.

1116
01:36:32,533 --> 01:36:35,024
''-Sorry.
-Would you like dinner, Mr. Douglas?''

1117
01:36:35,103 --> 01:36:37,333
-No. Bring me my lunch check.
-Certainly.

1118
01:36:37,405 --> 01:36:39,737
l think l'll eat out tonight.

1119
01:36:42,110 --> 01:36:46,137
''-Frank, bring me another.
-So soon? Where's the last one?''

1120
01:36:46,214 --> 01:36:49,945
lt vanished...
like Brigadoon.

1121
01:36:50,017 --> 01:36:51,951
''Like who, sir?''

1122
01:36:52,019 --> 01:36:54,681
That was the name
of my brother who ran away.

1123
01:36:59,527 --> 01:37:02,394
''Good evening, Mr. Albright.
Your table will be ready in a moment.''

1124
01:37:02,463 --> 01:37:04,397
''-Thank you, Peter.
-Tommy, Tommy.''

1125
01:37:04,465 --> 01:37:06,899
What's your opinion
about the Parker deal?

1126
01:37:06,968 --> 01:37:10,165
-l'll let you know tomorrow.
-l've got a real slant on it--

1127
01:37:10,238 --> 01:37:13,002
l'll tell you tomorrow.
l'll give you a call.

1128
01:37:13,074 --> 01:37:16,874
''Albright, how about that meeting
this morning? Was that great?''

1129
01:37:16,944 --> 01:37:19,139
-Great.
-Things were brought out in the open.

1130
01:37:19,213 --> 01:37:21,545
-Let in a lot of fresh air.
-Great.

1131
01:37:21,616 --> 01:37:24,244
-Do you like how l handled the old man?
-Great.

1132
01:37:24,318 --> 01:37:26,252
''Thanks, Albright.''

1133
01:37:29,190 --> 01:37:31,658
-Hi.
-Hi.

1134
01:37:31,726 --> 01:37:34,354
-lt's hot in here.
-lt's not the heat. lt's the humanity.

1135
01:37:34,428 --> 01:37:37,829
''-Good evening, Mr. Albright.
-Oh, thank you, Frank.''

1136
01:37:37,899 --> 01:37:40,299
-Have you seen Jane?
-She meeting you here?

1137
01:37:40,368 --> 01:37:43,360
-Yeah.
-l'll drink up and get outta here.

1138
01:37:43,437 --> 01:37:46,668
There's nothing a woman hates more
than her fianc's best friend.

1139
01:37:46,741 --> 01:37:50,700
He knows the secrets she's gonna spend
the rest of her life tryin' to find out.

1140
01:37:50,778 --> 01:37:54,236
-l've been dodging her for a month now.
-Don't worry about it.

1141
01:37:54,315 --> 01:37:57,648
''l always say, scratch the surface
of any woman and she'll enjoy it.''

1142
01:37:57,718 --> 01:38:00,448
-When are you getting married?
-l don't know.

1143
01:38:00,521 --> 01:38:04,048
-l don't know if l want to get married.
-Why?

1144
01:38:04,125 --> 01:38:06,889
''Because, old tank,
l'm in love with someone else...''

1145
01:38:06,961 --> 01:38:09,657
''and l ''''canna'''' get over it.''

1146
01:38:11,899 --> 01:38:16,302
''And the trouble is, because l can't
be with her, l can't be with anyone.''

1147
01:38:16,370 --> 01:38:18,634
So many things
remind me of her.

1148
01:38:18,706 --> 01:38:21,140
''l'll be talking with people,
and they might say one little word...''

1149
01:38:21,209 --> 01:38:25,236
''that opens the door
to a memory for me, and then...''

1150
01:38:25,313 --> 01:38:29,909
''l'm a few thousand miles away with--
well, you know.''

1151
01:38:29,984 --> 01:38:34,546
''But slowly l come back to the
conversation, they ask me a question...''

1152
01:38:34,622 --> 01:38:37,056
and l don't know what in the world
they've been talking about.

1153
01:38:37,124 --> 01:38:41,254
-l haven't heard a word.
-You must be fascinating company.

1154
01:38:41,329 --> 01:38:42,762
lt ain't easy.

1155
01:38:53,841 --> 01:38:55,775
''-Hello, Jane!
-Hello, Jane!''

1156
01:38:55,843 --> 01:38:58,437
''-You've certainly been elusive.
-Hello, Jeff.''

1157
01:38:58,512 --> 01:39:00,878
l've been up to my neck at the office.
Would you like a drink?

1158
01:39:00,948 --> 01:39:04,076
''Love one. An old-fashioned, please,
and would you bring it to the table?''

1159
01:39:04,151 --> 01:39:07,245
''-How are you, Jeff?
-Darling, it's been weeks.''

1160
01:39:07,321 --> 01:39:09,687
''-Fine, Jane. How are you?
-l'm sorry.''

1161
01:39:09,757 --> 01:39:11,987
''Oh, l've had a little cold,
but other than that--''

1162
01:39:12,059 --> 01:39:15,460
-But you could've called more often.
-l hate to eat and run.

1163
01:39:15,529 --> 01:39:17,622
''-Your table is ready, Mr. Albright.
-Thank you.''

1164
01:39:17,698 --> 01:39:19,666
-l'll call you later.
-Hello!

1165
01:39:19,734 --> 01:39:23,067
''Good-bye!
Frank, put it on the bill.''

1166
01:39:23,137 --> 01:39:26,470
''-Your bill, sir, is very high.
-So am l!''

1167
01:39:30,811 --> 01:39:32,904
''-Jane, you look fine.
-So do you.''

1168
01:39:32,980 --> 01:39:36,643
''-Would you care to order dinner now?
-No, we'll finish our drinks first.''

1169
01:39:36,717 --> 01:39:39,379
''Darling, l wish you'd been
with me over the weekend.''

1170
01:39:39,453 --> 01:39:42,980
''l went up to Connecticut, house hunting.
Saw the most wonderful place.''

1171
01:39:43,057 --> 01:39:47,289
''Rather interesting. Colonial,
and right on top of a beautiful hill.''

1172
01:39:47,361 --> 01:39:50,558
Through the heather

1173
01:39:50,631 --> 01:39:53,566
On the hill

1174
01:39:54,969 --> 01:39:57,301
The mornin' dew

1175
01:39:57,371 --> 01:40:01,569
ls blinkin' yonder

1176
01:40:01,642 --> 01:40:04,167
There's lazy music

1177
01:40:04,245 --> 01:40:08,204
On the rill

1178
01:40:08,282 --> 01:40:13,584
And all l want to do is wander

1179
01:40:13,654 --> 01:40:16,748
Through the heather--

1180
01:40:16,824 --> 01:40:19,418
''And l didn't think you'd
want to do that, would you?''

1181
01:40:19,493 --> 01:40:22,326
''Hmm? Uh, maybe.''

1182
01:40:22,396 --> 01:40:24,591
''You mean, you'd even consider it?''

1183
01:40:24,665 --> 01:40:26,064
What?

1184
01:40:26,133 --> 01:40:28,624
Commuting from
60 miles out of New York.

1185
01:40:28,703 --> 01:40:31,797
''-No, l wouldn't wanna do that.
-l didn't think so.''

1186
01:40:31,872 --> 01:40:34,636
And l told Mr. Bradville.

1187
01:40:34,709 --> 01:40:37,906
-Who?
-Herbert Bradville.

1188
01:40:39,313 --> 01:40:42,009
''-Who's he?
-Darling, he's the real estate man...''

1189
01:40:42,083 --> 01:40:44,916
l just told you
l've been working with.

1190
01:40:44,985 --> 01:40:49,649
''l told him you'd call, so please do.
l'm trying hard to arrange everything.''

1191
01:40:49,724 --> 01:40:53,751
''By the way, do you still want
Jeff to stand up for you?''

1192
01:40:53,828 --> 01:40:57,161
''Yes, if he can.''

1193
01:40:57,231 --> 01:40:58,664
Why?

1194
01:40:59,734 --> 01:41:03,568
Nothing. lt's just
he's so impossible these days.

1195
01:41:03,637 --> 01:41:06,105
Everybody's bored to death with him.

1196
01:41:06,173 --> 01:41:09,074
''Maybe l'm not interested
in everybody, Jane.''

1197
01:41:09,143 --> 01:41:13,705
''Well, you certainly have been antisocial
since you got back from Scotland.''

1198
01:41:13,781 --> 01:41:16,944
l thought for a while there was
something really bothering you.

1199
01:41:17,017 --> 01:41:19,076
You certainly wouldn't
keep me waiting and--

1200
01:41:19,153 --> 01:41:23,385
Waitin' for my dearie

1201
01:41:23,457 --> 01:41:27,655
And happy am l

1202
01:41:27,728 --> 01:41:30,094
To hold my heart

1203
01:41:30,164 --> 01:41:36,399
'Til he comes strollin' by

1204
01:41:36,470 --> 01:41:39,166
''-Give me a ring, won't you?
-Oh, of course.''

1205
01:41:39,240 --> 01:41:43,142
'' When he comes, my dearie''

1206
01:41:43,210 --> 01:41:47,442
One look and l'll know

1207
01:41:47,515 --> 01:41:49,915
That he's the dearie

1208
01:41:49,984 --> 01:41:54,785
l've been wantin' so

1209
01:41:54,855 --> 01:41:58,450
''-When l see you wander around like--
-No, Jane. No.''

1210
01:41:58,526 --> 01:42:02,121
-No what?
-There won't be a wedding next month.

1211
01:42:02,196 --> 01:42:05,597
''-Do you mean you're postponing it again?
-No, Jane, l'm not postponing it.''

1212
01:42:05,666 --> 01:42:08,863
-l'm calling it off for good.
-Calling it off?

1213
01:42:08,936 --> 01:42:11,962
''Jane, l'm sorry.
You've been wonderful, darling.''

1214
01:42:12,039 --> 01:42:15,497
''lt's not your fault, but something
strange happened to me a few months ago.''

1215
01:42:15,576 --> 01:42:18,568
''l can't explain it,
but l just don't fit here anymore.''

1216
01:42:18,646 --> 01:42:21,240
You've gone clean out of your mind.

1217
01:42:21,315 --> 01:42:24,944
We can't stand here and talk about it.
Let's go home and--

1218
